# maritime-flow

## Project Overview
Maritime vessel tracking and trade flow inference system.
Processes real-time AIS (Automatic Identification System) 
data from vessels to detect anomalous behaviour and infer 
trade flows. Built as a learning project for Flink, 
SedonaFlink, Kafka, and remote sensing integration.

## Repository Structure
maritime-flow/
├── ais-collector/     WebSocket client, reads from aisstream.io, 
│                      writes raw JSON to Kafka
├── ais-filter/        Coarse stateless filter, runs on Hetzner
├── ais-smartfilter/   Proximity and watchlist aware filter, 
│                      runs on Minisforum
├── ais-merge/         Multi-source deduplication
├── ais-analyser/      Main Flink + SedonaFlink processing app
├── common/            Shared models, constants, enums
├── reference-data/    PostGIS layer loading scripts
└── k8s/               K3s deployment manifests

## Language and Build
- Java 17
- Maven, no parent pom — each module is an independent 
  Maven project
- No Gradle suggestions
- No Kotlin suggestions

## Core Technology Stack
- Apache Flink — stream processing engine
- Apache SedonaFlink — spatial operations on Flink streams
- Redpanda — Kafka-compatible message broker (used everywhere,
  referred to as Kafka in code)
- PostgreSQL + PostGIS — spatial reference layers and 
  vessel state document store (JSONB)
- OkHttp — WebSocket client in ais-collector
- Jackson — JSON serialisation/deserialisation
- Protobuf — internal Kafka event topics only
- MapLibre GL JS — globe frontend (future)
- Sentinel/Copernicus API — SAR imagery integration (future)

## Infrastructure
Hetzner VPS (always on):
- ais-collector, ais-filter
- Redpanda: topics ais.aisstream, ais.coarse (7 day retention)

Minisforum CachyOS (usually on):
- All other modules
- Redpanda: long term archive 30+ days
- MirrorMaker 2: replicates from Hetzner
- K3s: runs ais-analyser, PostGIS, frontend

## Kafka Topics
Raw:      ais.aisstream    (JSON, from aisstream.io)
          ais.aishub       (JSON, future)
          ais.local        (JSON, future receiver)
Filtered: ais.coarse       (JSON, stateless filtered)
          ais.filtered     (JSON, smart filtered)
Merged:   ais.merged       (JSON, deduplicated, source-tagged)
Events:   events.anomalies     (Protobuf)
          events.sar_triggers  (Protobuf)
          events.watchlist     (Protobuf)

## Serialisation Rules
- Raw AIS topics: JSON only — schema is external and unstable
- Internal event topics: Protobuf
- Document state: PostgreSQL JSONB
- Spatial reference data: PostGIS native geometry
- Never transcode raw AIS to Protobuf

## ais-collector Specifics
- OkHttp WebSocket client
- Pluggable source interface: AisMessageSource, AisMessageHandler
- Auto-reconnect on disconnect (aisstream disconnects every ~2min)
- Defensive JSON deserialisation — aisstream API is beta/unstable,
  handle unknown fields gracefully, never use strict typing
- Stamp source name on every message before Kafka
- Current implementation: AisStreamWebSocketSource

## ais-analyser Specifics
- Flink StreamExecutionEnvironment
- SedonaFlink registered for spatial operations
- Event-time processing with watermarks — always use event 
  timestamps from AIS messages, never processing time
- RocksDB state backend
- State TTL: 48-72 hours for normal vessels
- Watchlisted vessels: TTL suppressed
- Two-tier state: RocksDB (hot) → PostgreSQL JSONB (cold)
- On vessel reappearance: query PostgreSQL, rehydrate RocksDB
- Watermark lag: keep tight, ~60 seconds

## Detection Layers (ais-analyser)
Layer 1: Physical plausibility
         Speed vs vessel-type max speed (from VesselType enum)
         Position on land = hard anomaly
Layer 2: Gap/dark vessel detection
         Event-time gap timers per vessel
         Cross-check against coverage zone
Layer 3: Multi-vessel coherence
         DBSCAN clustering of simultaneous anomalies
         Temporal persistence required before alerting
Layer 4: STS transfer detection
         Proximity detection, near-zero speed, extended duration
Layer 5: IMO disappearance tracking
         Per-IMO timer, escalating score on non-reappearance

## Anomaly Scoring
- Fuzzy confidence scores, not binary thresholds
- All signals produce 0.0-1.0 scores with weights
- Scores accumulate in per-vessel Flink state
- Alert when score exceeds threshold AND sustained over time window
- VesselAnomalyState holds per-signal scores + aggregate

## PostgreSQL JSONB Collections
- vessels          enriched per-vessel state, static history
- watchlist        uncertainty cones + geometry column
- trade_flows      cargo movement inferences
- anomaly_history  scored events over time

## PostGIS Reference Layers
- coastline              land/sea boundary
- ports                  port polygons
- anchorages             anchorage polygons
- coverage_buffer        200km coastal coverage zone
- navigable_water        for realistic routing distances

## Spatial Operations
- Always use ST_DistanceSphere for speed/distance calculations
- Coordinates always WGS84 (EPSG:4326)
- AIS data is lon/lat order — be explicit when constructing points
- Broadcast state pattern for static polygon lookups in Flink
- Position on land = spoofing signal, do NOT filter it out

## Common Module Contents
- AisMessage, PositionReport, ShipStaticData (Jackson models)
- KafkaTopics constants class
- Protobuf generated classes
- VesselType enum with maxSpeedKnots
- Geographic constants

## Key Design Decisions
- Flink not Spark — stateful streaming, event-time correctness
  during Minisforum offline/catch-up scenarios
- Redpanda everywhere — Kafka-compatible, lighter than Kafka
- No MongoDB — PostgreSQL JSONB sufficient for document storage
- No parent pom — independent Maven modules
- Raw JSON preserved in Kafka — never transcode external data
- Position on land is anomaly signal, not filter candidate
- UN sanctions only — unilateral sanctions not treated as law
- Naming: use behavioural/observational language, not judgement
  language (anomalous behaviour, not violation)

## What This Project Is NOT
- Not a sanctions enforcement tool
- Not dependent on any paid data source
- Not real-time in the millisecond sense — seconds to minutes 
  latency is acceptable
- Not attempting global coverage — coastal coverage accepted

## Current Development State
- Planning phase complete
- ais-collector: exploratory phase
  Initial goal: connect to aisstream.io, print messages 
  to console, understand message types and field population
- All other modules: not yet started
